<div id="t1">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">1</div><div><div class="ttitle">Data Science &amp; Types of Data</div><div class="tsub">Structured · Semi-structured · Unstructured · Data Streams · Qualitative · Quantitative</div></div><span class="badge br">ALL 8 Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'22, June'23, Dec'23, Dec'24, June'24, June'25, Dec'25 — every single paper</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Data Science combines computing, statistics, and domain knowledge to find patterns in data. Not all data looks the same — some sits neatly in tables (structured), some has tags but no fixed format (semi-structured), some has zero structure (unstructured), and some keeps flowing continuously without stopping (data streams). Knowing the type decides which tools you use.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Multi-disciplinary science</span><span class="kw">Rows and columns</span><span class="kw">Fixed schema</span><span class="kw">Tags or key-value pairs</span><span class="kw">No defined structure</span><span class="kw">Continuous unbounded</span><span class="kw">Real-time processing</span><span class="kw">SQL queryable</span><span class="kw">Categories with no numeric value</span><span class="kw">Numeric and measurable</span><span class="kw">Discrete vs Continuous</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer — Core Points Only</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Types of Data — Quick Version</span><span class="marks5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Data Science is a <span class="kh">multi-disciplinary science</span> combining computing, statistics, and domain knowledge to extract knowledge from data.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Structured Data:</strong> <span class="kh">Rows and columns</span> with <span class="kh">fixed schema</span>. Example: Bank database table.</li>
<li><strong>Semi-Structured Data:</strong> Uses <span class="kh">tags or key-value pairs</span>, no strict format. Example: XML, JSON files.</li>
<li><strong>Unstructured Data:</strong> <span class="kh">No defined structure</span>. Example: Photos, videos, social media posts.</li>
<li><strong>Data Streams:</strong> <span class="kh">Continuous unbounded</span> data needing <span class="kh">real-time processing</span>. Example: Stock prices, sensor feeds.</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer — With Table</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Types of Data — Detailed with Comparison Table</span><span class="marks10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Data Science is a <span class="kh">multi-disciplinary science</span> combining computing, statistics, and domain knowledge to extract useful knowledge from data. Data used in Data Science can be classified into four major types based on structure:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Type</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Structured Data</strong></td><td>Organised in <span class="kh">rows and columns</span> with a <span class="kh">fixed schema</span>. Easily queried using SQL.</td><td>Bank customer table: CustomerID, Name, Balance</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Semi-Structured Data</strong></td><td>Has partial structure using <span class="kh">tags or key-value pairs</span> but no strict fixed format.</td><td>XML files, JSON objects, email headers</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Unstructured Data</strong></td><td>Has <span class="kh">no defined structure</span> at all. Largest volume of data generated today.</td><td>Social media posts, photos, videos, audio</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Data Streams</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Continuous unbounded</span> data generated over time, requiring <span class="kh">real-time processing</span> since it cannot all be stored.</td><td>Stock prices, sensor data, Twitter feeds</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Qualitative vs Quantitative Data:</strong> Qualitative data describes <span class="kh">categories with no numeric value</span> — e.g. gender, colour, brand name. Quantitative data is <span class="kh">numeric and measurable</span> — e.g. height, salary, age. Quantitative data is further split into <span class="kh">Discrete vs Continuous</span> — Discrete is countable in whole numbers (number of children), Continuous can take any value in a range (height, weight).</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 20-Mark Answer — Full Coverage with Applications</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Data Science, Types of Data, and Applications — Complete</span><span class="marks20">20 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Data Science is a <span class="kh">multi-disciplinary science</span> that combines computing, mathematics, statistics, and domain knowledge to collect, clean, process, and analyse data in order to generate knowledge useful for decision making.</p>
<p><strong>Four Types of Data (by structure):</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Type</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Structured</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Rows and columns</span>, <span class="kh">fixed schema</span>, <span class="kh">SQL queryable</span></td><td>Bank customer table</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Semi-Structured</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Tags or key-value pairs</span>, flexible format</td><td>XML, JSON, server logs</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Unstructured</strong></td><td><span class="kh">No defined structure</span>, hardest to process</td><td>Images, videos, WhatsApp chats</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Data Streams</strong></td><td><span class="kh">Continuous unbounded</span>, needs <span class="kh">real-time processing</span></td><td>IoT sensors, live stock prices</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Qualitative vs Quantitative Data:</strong> Qualitative = <span class="kh">categories with no numeric value</span> (Nominal: no order e.g. eye colour; Ordinal: has order e.g. grades). Quantitative = <span class="kh">numeric and measurable</span> (Interval: equal gaps no true zero e.g. temperature °C; Ratio: equal gaps with true zero e.g. weight, height). Quantitative splits further into <span class="kh">Discrete vs Continuous</span>.</p>
<p><strong>Applications of Data Science:</strong> Spam detection (classifying emails using word patterns), Financial fraud detection (flagging suspicious transactions), Product recommendation (Amazon/Flipkart suggesting items), Healthcare (tumour detection from medical images), Smart transport (real-time route optimisation using traffic data), Web search ranking.</p>
<p><strong>Why Data Science Matters:</strong> Organisations generate massive volumes of mixed-type data daily. Recognising which type you're working with determines storage choice (SQL vs NoSQL), processing approach (batch vs stream), and the analytical techniques applicable — making this classification the very first decision point in any data science project.</p>
</div></div>
</div>

