<!-- T7 BAYES -->
<div id="t7">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">2</div><div><div class="ttitle">Bayes Theorem &amp; Conditional Probability</div><div class="tsub">Formula · Components · Example · Significance Testing</div></div><span class="badge by">4+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'23, Dec'24, June'24, Dec'25 — appears almost every cycle, simple guaranteed marks</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Conditional Probability asks: "Given X already happened, what's the chance Y happens too?" Bayes Theorem flips this around — it lets you update your belief about a cause once you've observed an effect. Like a doctor: given a positive test result (effect), what's the actual probability the patient has the disease (cause)?</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">P(A given B)</span><span class="kw">Prior probability</span><span class="kw">Posterior probability</span><span class="kw">Likelihood</span><span class="kw">Updates belief with new evidence</span><span class="kw">Independent events</span><span class="kw">Joint probability</span><span class="kw">Null hypothesis</span><span class="kw">p-value</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer — Core</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Bayes Theorem — Quick Version</span><span class="marks5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Conditional Probability <span class="kh">P(A given B)</span> is the probability of A occurring given B has already occurred.</p>
<div class="formula">P(A|B) = P(A ∩ B) / P(B)

Bayes Theorem: P(A|B) = [P(B|A) × P(A)] / P(B)</div>
<p>Bayes Theorem <span class="kh">updates belief with new evidence</span> — it lets us calculate <span class="kh">posterior probability</span> from <span class="kh">prior probability</span> and <span class="kh">likelihood</span>.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer — With Example</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Bayes Theorem — Formula and Worked Example</span><span class="marks10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Conditional Probability <span class="kh">P(A given B)</span> is the probability of event A occurring given that event B has already occurred.</p>
<div class="formula">P(A|B) = P(A ∩ B) / P(B)

Bayes Theorem:
P(A|B) = [P(B|A) × P(A)] / P(B)

P(A) = Prior probability (belief before evidence)
P(A|B) = Posterior probability (belief after evidence B)
P(B|A) = Likelihood (probability of evidence given A is true)</div>
<p><strong>Worked Example:</strong> Bag A has 5 green + 5 red balls. Bag B has 3 green + 7 red balls. A ball is drawn at random from a randomly chosen bag and found to be red. What is the probability it came from Bag B?</p>
<div class="formula">P(B|Red) = [P(Red|B) × P(B)] / P(Red)
         = [0.7 × 0.5] / [(0.5×0.5)+(0.5×0.7)]
         = 0.35 / 0.6 = 0.583 (58.3%)</div>
<p>This forms the foundation of spam filters, medical diagnosis systems, and the Naive Bayes machine learning classifier.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 20-Mark Answer — With Significance Testing</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Bayes Theorem + Steps of Significance Testing — Complete</span><span class="marks20">20 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Conditional Probability <span class="kh">P(A given B)</span> is the probability of A occurring given B has already occurred. Bayes Theorem allows us to reverse a conditional probability — moving from P(B|A) to P(A|B) — and is central to <span class="kh">updates belief with new evidence</span>.</p>
<div class="formula">P(A|B) = [P(B|A) × P(A)] / P(B)
P(A) = Prior, P(A|B) = Posterior, P(B|A) = Likelihood</div>
<p>Worked Example (Bag A/B with red/green balls) gives P(B|Red) = 58.3% — shown step by step above using the formula.</p>
<p>If events A and B are <span class="kh">independent events</span>, then P(A∩B) = P(A) × P(B), and conditional probability simplifies because B gives no new information about A. <span class="kh">Joint probability</span> P(A∩B) is the probability both events happen together.</p>
<p><strong>Steps of Significance Testing (Hypothesis Testing):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Step 1:</strong> State the <span class="kh">null hypothesis</span> (H₀ — no effect/difference) and alternative hypothesis (Hₐ — effect exists)</li>
<li><strong>Step 2:</strong> Choose significance level (commonly α = 0.05)</li>
<li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Collect sample data and compute the test statistic</li>
<li><strong>Step 4:</strong> Calculate the <span class="kh">p-value</span> from the test statistic</li>
<li><strong>Step 5:</strong> Decision rule — if p-value &lt; α, reject H₀ (result is statistically significant); if p-value ≥ α, fail to reject H₀</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> Testing if a new drug improves recovery time. H₀: no difference in recovery time. After clinical trial, p-value = 0.03 &lt; 0.05 → reject H₀ → the drug does have a statistically significant effect.</p>
</div></div>
</div>

