<p><strong>NoSQL vs RDBMS:</strong> RDBMS requires fixed schema and strong ACID consistency; NoSQL is flexible, <span class="kh">schema-less</span>, and trades strict consistency for <span class="kh">high availability</span> and horizontal scale — per the <span class="kh">CAP Theorem</span>, distributed systems can guarantee only 2 of Consistency, Availability, Partition tolerance.</p>
<p><strong>Graph Databases — Neo4j vs OrientDB:</strong> Both store data as nodes and relationships rather than tables. Neo4j is a pure graph database optimised specifically for graph traversal queries (Cypher query language), widely used and mature. OrientDB is a multi-model database supporting graph, document, key-value, and object models together — more flexible but can be less specialised/optimised than Neo4j for pure graph workloads. Neo4j generally offers faster graph traversal performance; OrientDB offers more flexibility when an application needs multiple data models in one system.</p>
