<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'22, June'23, June'24, Dec'24, June'25, Dec'25 — guaranteed every attempt</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>PageRank decides which web pages are most important by treating every hyperlink as a "vote." A page linked by many important pages is itself important. Web pages can form traps (loops) or dead ends that confuse the random-walking algorithm, so Google's solution is "random teleportation."</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Importance of web pages</span><span class="kw">Directed graph</span><span class="kw">Random walk</span><span class="kw">Out-degree</span><span class="kw">Dead End Problem</span><span class="kw">Spider Trap Problem</span><span class="kw">Random teleportation</span><span class="kw">Damping factor (β = 0.85)</span><span class="kw">Topic-Sensitive PageRank</span><span class="kw">Link Spam / Spam Farms</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer — Core Concept Only</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>PageRank — Quick Version</span><span class="marks5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>PageRank computes the <span class="kh">importance of web pages</span> by representing the web as a <span class="kh">directed graph</span> — a link from an important page counts as a stronger vote.</p>
<div class="formula">PageRank(j) = Σ [PageRank(i) / Out-degree(i)] for all pages i linking to j</div>
<p><strong>Random Walk Model:</strong> A surfer clicks random links forever; the fraction of time spent on each page = its PageRank score. Used by search engines to rank pages — pages with higher PageRank appear higher in search results.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer — With Dead End and Spider Trap</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>PageRank — Problems and Solutions</span><span class="marks10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>PageRank computes the <span class="kh">importance of web pages</span> via a <span class="kh">directed graph</span> model and the <span class="kh">random walk</span> concept.</p>
<div class="formula">PageRank(j) = Σ [PageRank(i) / Out-degree(i)] for all pages i linking to j</div>
<table>
<tr><th>Problem</th><th>What Happens</th><th>Solution</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Dead End Problem</strong></td><td>A page with NO outgoing links — walker gets stuck, PageRank leaks away</td><td><span class="kh">Random teleportation</span> — walker jumps to a random page when stuck</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Spider Trap Problem</strong></td><td>A closed loop of pages linking only to each other — walker gets trapped, absorbs all PageRank</td><td>With <span class="kh">damping factor (β = 0.85)</span>, walker follows a link 85% of time, teleports 15% of time — breaking any loop</td></tr>
</table>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 20-Mark Answer — Complete with Topic-Sensitive and Link Spam</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>PageRank — Complete: All Mechanisms, Spam, Justification</span><span class="marks20">20 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>PageRank computes the <span class="kh">importance of web pages</span> using a <span class="kh">directed graph</span> representation — each page is a node, each hyperlink a directed edge. A link from an important page counts as a stronger vote of confidence.</p>
<div class="formula">PageRank(j) = Σ [PageRank(i) / Out-degree(i)] for all pages i linking to j

Random Walk Model: A surfer clicks random links forever.
Fraction of time on each page = its PageRank score.</div>
<p><strong>Two Major Problems and Solutions:</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Problem</th><th>What Happens</th><th>Solution</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Dead End</strong></td><td>No outgoing links — PageRank leaks and disappears system-wide</td><td><span class="kh">Random teleportation</span> when stuck</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Spider Trap</strong></td><td>Closed loop absorbs all PageRank permanently</td><td><span class="kh">Damping factor (β = 0.85)</span> — follow link 85%, teleport randomly 15%</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Topic-Sensitive PageRank:</strong> Instead of teleporting to ANY random page, teleportation is restricted to pages within a specific topic set — producing personalised, topic-biased rankings. Useful when the same query should rank differently for different user interests.</p>
<p><strong>Link Spamming:</strong> Creating fake <span class="kh">Spam Farms</span> — networks of pages all linking to a target page to artificially boost its rank. Solution: Google analyses anchor text from genuine external links rather than trusting self-claims, and penalises detected spam farm patterns through algorithmic detection (e.g., TrustRank seeding from known trustworthy pages).</p>
<p><strong>Justification: "PageRank is trustworthy to retrieve legitimate webpages"</strong> — Because PageRank weighs votes by the importance of the voter (not just raw link count), it is naturally resistant to simple manipulation (one spam page linking doesn't help much). Combined with damping factor solutions for traps/dead-ends and anti-spam detection, it consistently surfaces pages that are genuinely well-regarded across the web's link structure — making it a robust signal despite ongoing spam attempts.</p>
<p><strong>Different Mechanisms of Finding PageRank:</strong> Power Iteration Method (iteratively multiply rank vector by the transition matrix until convergence), Random Walk simulation (Monte Carlo approach), and Matrix-based computation using the Google Matrix (combines link structure with the damping/teleportation factor).</p>
</div></div>
</div>

