<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>A Decision Tree asks yes/no questions to classify data — like a flowchart. Entropy measures how mixed up (impure) a group of data is; Information Gain measures how much a question reduces that confusion. A Random Forest is many decision trees voting together — reducing the risk of one tree's mistakes.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Categorical variable</span><span class="kw">Continuous variable</span><span class="kw">Entropy = impurity measure</span><span class="kw">Information Gain</span><span class="kw">Root node, leaf node</span><span class="kw">Pruning</span><span class="kw">Overfitting</span><span class="kw">Ensemble of trees</span><span class="kw">Bagging</span><span class="kw">Majority voting</span><span class="kw">Partitioning</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer — Core</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Decision Trees — Quick Version</span><span class="marks5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>A Decision Tree splits data repeatedly based on feature values to classify, working with <span class="kh">categorical variable</span> and <span class="kh">continuous variable</span> data. <span class="kh">Entropy = impurity measure</span>; <span class="kh">Information Gain</span> measures entropy reduction from a split — the tree picks the highest-gain split at each node, from <span class="kh">root node</span> to <span class="kh">leaf node</span>.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer — With Formulas</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Decision Trees — Entropy, Information Gain, Pruning</span><span class="marks10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>A Decision Tree is a flowchart-like model splitting data based on feature values to classify, handling both <span class="kh">categorical variable</span> (discrete, e.g. Yes/No) and <span class="kh">continuous variable</span> (numeric range, e.g. Age) data.</p>
<div class="formula">Entropy(S) = −Σ pᵢ log₂(pᵢ)
Information Gain = Entropy(parent) − Weighted Average Entropy(children)</div>
<p><span class="kh">Pruning</span> removes branches with little predictive power, preventing <span class="kh">overfitting</span> (memorising training data instead of generalising). <span class="kh">Partitioning</span> is the process of repeatedly splitting the dataset at each node based on the feature/threshold that gives maximum Information Gain.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 20-Mark Answer — Complete with Random Forest Comparison</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Decision Trees, Random Forest — Complete Comparison</span><span class="marks20">20 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>A Decision Tree is a flowchart-like model that splits data repeatedly based on feature values to reach a classification decision, handling <span class="kh">categorical variable</span> and <span class="kh">continuous variable</span> data alike.</p>
<p><strong>Entropy and Information Gain:</strong> <span class="kh">Entropy = impurity measure</span> — quantifies how mixed the classes are (0 = pure, 1 = max disorder). <span class="kh">Information Gain</span> measures entropy reduction from a split. The tree picks the highest-gain split at each step, from <span class="kh">root node</span> down to <span class="kh">leaf nodes</span>.</p>
<div class="formula">Entropy(S) = −Σ pᵢ log₂(pᵢ)
Information Gain = Entropy(parent) − Weighted Average Entropy(children)</div>
<p><strong>Role of Partitioning, Pruning, Tree Selection:</strong> <span class="kh">Partitioning</span> repeatedly splits the dataset at each node using the feature/threshold giving maximum Information Gain, building the tree top-down. <span class="kh">Pruning</span> removes branches adding little predictive value, preventing <span class="kh">overfitting</span> (post-pruning trims after full growth; pre-pruning stops growth early using thresholds). Tree selection compares candidate trees (e.g. via cross-validation) to pick the one generalising best to unseen data.</p>
<p><strong>Random Forest vs Decision Tree:</strong></p>
<table>
<tr><th>Feature</th><th>Decision Tree</th><th>Random Forest</th></tr>
<tr><td>Structure</td><td>Single tree</td><td><span class="kh">Ensemble of trees</span> — many trees combined</td></tr>
<tr><td>Method</td><td>One model, one decision path</td><td><span class="kh">Bagging</span> — each tree trained on random data/feature subset</td></tr>
<tr><td>Final Decision</td><td>Direct tree output</td><td><span class="kh">Majority voting</span> across all trees</td></tr>
<tr><td>Overfitting Risk</td><td>High</td><td>Low — averaging reduces overfitting</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>Pseudo-code for Random Forest:</strong></p>
<div class="formula">for i = 1 to N trees:
    sample = bootstrap_sample(training_data)
    tree[i] = build_decision_tree(sample, random_feature_subset)
prediction = majority_vote(tree[1], tree[2], ..., tree[N])</div>
</div></div>
</div>

