<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Clustering groups similar data points together without knowing the "correct" answer in advance — unlike classification where you have labelled categories. K-means is the most common clustering algorithm: pick K cluster centers, assign each point to its nearest center, then update centers and repeat until stable.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Unsupervised learning</span><span class="kw">Groups similar data points</span><span class="kw">K centroids</span><span class="kw">Iterative reassignment</span><span class="kw">Hierarchical clustering</span><span class="kw">Partitional clustering</span><span class="kw">Density-based clustering</span><span class="kw">Elbow method</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer — Core</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Clustering — Quick Version</span><span class="marks5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Clustering is an <span class="kh">unsupervised learning</span> technique that <span class="kh">groups similar data points</span> together without predefined labels.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Partitional clustering</strong> (e.g. K-means) — divides data into K non-overlapping groups</li>
<li><strong>Hierarchical clustering</strong> — builds a tree of nested clusters (dendrogram)</li>
<li><strong>Density-based clustering</strong> (e.g. DBSCAN) — groups based on density of points</li>
</ul>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer — K-means with R Steps</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Clustering Types and K-means Algorithm with R</span><span class="marks10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p>Clustering is an <span class="kh">unsupervised learning</span> technique that <span class="kh">groups similar data points</span> together based on feature similarity, without using pre-labelled categories.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Type</th><th>How it Works</th><th>Example</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Partitional</strong></td><td>Divides data into K non-overlapping groups around <span class="kh">K centroids</span></td><td>K-means</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Hierarchical</strong></td><td>Builds nested cluster tree (dendrogram) — agglomerative (bottom-up) or divisive (top-down)</td><td>Customer segmentation trees</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Density-based</strong></td><td>Groups points based on density, can find arbitrarily shaped clusters</td><td>DBSCAN</td></tr>
</table>
<p><strong>K-means Algorithm Steps:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Choose number of clusters K</li>
<li>Randomly initialise K <span class="kh">K centroids</span></li>
<li>Assign each data point to its nearest centroid</li>
<li><span class="kh">Iterative reassignment</span> — recompute centroids as the mean of assigned points, repeat assignment until centroids stop moving</li>
</ul>
<div class="formula">R: kmeans_result &lt;- kmeans(data, centers=K, nstart=25)
   print(kmeans_result$cluster)   # cluster assignment per point</div>
<p>The <span class="kh">Elbow method</span> helps choose the optimal K by plotting within-cluster variance against different K values and picking the "elbow" point where improvement slows down.</p>
</div></div>
</div>

<!-- T19 ASSOCIATION + TIME SERIES -->
<div id="t19">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">17</div><div><div class="ttitle">Association Rules &amp; Time Series Analysis</div><div class="tsub">Support, Confidence, Lift · Time Series Components</div></div><span class="badge by">Must Read — Recurring Short Notes</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'24 (short note), June'23 ("Time series analysis" steps using R) — both appeared as short-note questions worth 5 marks each</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>Association Rules find "people who bought X also bought Y" patterns — the classic supermarket basket analysis. Time Series Analysis studies data points collected over time (like monthly sales) to spot trends, seasonality, and make forecasts.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Support</span><span class="kw">Confidence</span><span class="kw">Lift</span><span class="kw">Market basket analysis</span><span class="kw">Trend component</span><span class="kw">Seasonality component</span><span class="kw">Cyclic component</span><span class="kw">Irregular/Random component</span><span class="kw">Forecasting</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer — Both Topics, Core</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Association Rules and Time Series — Quick Version</span><span class="marks5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p><strong>Association Rules</strong> discover relationships between items in transaction data — <span class="kh">market basket analysis</span>. Measured using <span class="kh">Support</span> (how frequently items appear together), <span class="kh">Confidence</span> (how often the rule is true), and <span class="kh">Lift</span> (how much more likely together vs independently).</p>
<p><strong>Time Series Analysis</strong> studies data points indexed by time to identify the <span class="kh">Trend component</span> (long-term direction) and <span class="kh">Seasonality component</span> (repeating patterns) for <span class="kh">Forecasting</span> future values.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer — With Formulas and R Steps</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Association Rules (Formulas) + Time Series (R Steps)</span><span class="marks10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p><strong>Association Rules</strong> identify patterns like "if a customer buys bread, they also buy butter" — the foundation of <span class="kh">market basket analysis</span>.</p>
<div class="formula">Support(A→B)    = (Transactions containing A and B) / (Total transactions)
Confidence(A→B) = (Transactions containing A and B) / (Transactions containing A)
Lift(A→B)       = Confidence(A→B) / Support(B)</div>
<p>Lift &gt; 1 means A and B occur together more often than expected by chance — a genuinely useful rule.</p>
<p><strong>Time Series Analysis</strong> breaks down time-indexed data into four components:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Trend component:</strong> Long-term upward or downward direction</li>
<li><strong>Seasonality component:</strong> Regular repeating patterns (e.g. higher sales every December)</li>
<li><strong>Cyclic component:</strong> Longer irregular fluctuations (e.g. economic cycles)</li>
<li><strong>Irregular/Random component:</strong> Unpredictable noise</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>R Steps for Time Series Analysis:</strong></p>
<div class="formula">ts_data &lt;- ts(sales_data, frequency=12, start=c(2020,1))
plot(ts_data)                          # visualize the series
decomposed &lt;- decompose(ts_data)        # split into trend/season/random
plot(decomposed)
forecast_model &lt;- forecast::auto.arima(ts_data)
predict(forecast_model, n.ahead=12)     # forecast next 12 periods</div>
<p>This is used for <span class="kh">Forecasting</span> future values based on historical patterns — e.g., predicting next quarter's sales.</p>
</div></div>
</div>
<!-- T15 VISUALIZATION -->
<div id="t15">
<div class="topic"><div class="tnum">18</div><div><div class="ttitle">Box Plot, Scatter Plot, Heat Map</div><div class="tsub">Uses · Best Practices · Differences · Pair Plot</div></div><span class="badge br">7+ Papers</span></div>
<div class="pyq">📋 Asked in: Dec'22, June'23, Dec'23, June'24, Dec'24, June'25, Dec'25 — EVERY single paper, easiest guaranteed marks</div>
<div class="sec">💡 Understand It Simply</div>
<div class="understand"><div class="ul">What it actually means</div><p>The three most frequently asked visualization types. Box Plot shows spread and outliers of one variable using 5 key numbers. Scatter Plot shows the relationship between two variables as dots. Heat Map shows patterns across two categories using colour intensity.</p></div>
<div class="sec">🔑 Keywords to Memorise</div>
<div class="keywords"><div class="kl">These words MUST appear in your answer</div>
<div class="kw-grid"><span class="kw">Five-number summary</span><span class="kw">Whiskers</span><span class="kw">Outliers</span><span class="kw">Interquartile Range (IQR)</span><span class="kw">Two quantitative variables</span><span class="kw">Correlation</span><span class="kw">Trend line</span><span class="kw">Colour intensity</span><span class="kw">Two-dimensional patterns</span><span class="kw">Pair Plot diagonal/off-diagonal</span></div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 5-Mark Answer — Core (pick any one chart asked)</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Box Plot / Scatter / Heat Map — Quick Version</span><span class="marks5">5 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p><strong>Box Plot:</strong> Shows the <span class="kh">five-number summary</span> (Min, Q1, Median, Q3, Max). Box covers middle 50% (<span class="kh">Interquartile Range (IQR)</span>); <span class="kh">whiskers</span> extend to min/max within 1.5×IQR; points beyond are <span class="kh">outliers</span>.</p>
<p><strong>Scatter Plot:</strong> Plots <span class="kh">two quantitative variables</span> as points, revealing <span class="kh">correlation</span>. A <span class="kh">trend line</span> shows the relationship direction.</p>
<p><strong>Heat Map:</strong> Uses <span class="kh">colour intensity</span> to show value magnitude across a grid, revealing <span class="kh">two-dimensional patterns</span> at a glance.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 10-Mark Answer — All Three Compared</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Box Plot, Scatter Plot, Heat Map — Full Comparison</span><span class="marks10">10 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p><strong>Box Plot</strong> displays the <span class="kh">five-number summary</span> — Min, Q1, Median, Q3, Max. The box covers the middle 50% (<span class="kh">Interquartile Range (IQR)</span>); <span class="kh">whiskers</span> extend to min/max within 1.5×IQR; points beyond are flagged as <span class="kh">outliers</span>. Use: comparing distributions across categories.</p>
<p><strong>Scatter Plot</strong> plots <span class="kh">two quantitative variables</span> as (x,y) points, revealing <span class="kh">correlation</span> — positive, negative, or none. A <span class="kh">trend line</span> can be overlaid. Use: studying relationships, e.g., temperature vs ice cream sales.</p>
<p><strong>Heat Map</strong> uses <span class="kh">colour intensity</span> to show value magnitude across a 2D grid, revealing <span class="kh">two-dimensional patterns</span> at a glance. Use: sales across months and regions simultaneously.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Chart</th><th>Best For</th><th>Key Difference</th></tr>
<tr><td>Box Plot</td><td>Distribution + outliers of ONE variable across groups</td><td>Summary statistics, not individual points</td></tr>
<tr><td>Scatter Plot</td><td>Relationship between TWO continuous variables</td><td>Shows every individual data point</td></tr>
<tr><td>Heat Map</td><td>Patterns across TWO categorical dimensions</td><td>Uses colour, not position, to show value</td></tr>
</table>
</div></div>

<div class="sec">✍ 20-Mark Answer — Complete with R Syntax and Pair Plot</div>
<div class="ans-card"><div class="ans-head"><span>Visualization Complete: Box/Scatter/Heat Map + Pair Plot + R Code</span><span class="marks20">20 Marks</span></div>
<div class="ans-body">
<p><strong>Box Plot</strong> displays the <span class="kh">five-number summary</span> (Min, Q1, Median, Q3, Max). Box = middle 50% (<span class="kh">Interquartile Range (IQR)</span>); <span class="kh">whiskers</span> extend to 1.5×IQR; beyond = <span class="kh">outliers</span>. Best for comparing distributions and spotting skewness across groups.</p>
<p><strong>Scatter Plot</strong> plots <span class="kh">two quantitative variables</span>, revealing <span class="kh">correlation</span> (positive/negative/none) with an optional <span class="kh">trend line</span>. Best for studying relationships between continuous variables.</p>
<p><strong>Heat Map</strong> uses <span class="kh">colour intensity</span> for magnitude across a 2D grid, showing <span class="kh">two-dimensional patterns</span> instantly. Best for cross-tabulated data like sales-by-region-by-month.</p>
<p><strong>Pair Plot:</strong> An m×m grid of subplots for m variables. The <span class="kh">Pair Plot diagonal/off-diagonal</span> structure — diagonal shows histograms of each individual variable; off-diagonal shows scatter plots of every variable pair. Excellent for quickly exploring all pairwise relationships in one view at the start of analysis.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Chart</th><th>Best For</th><th>R Syntax</th></tr>
<tr><td>Box Plot</td><td>Outlier detection, group comparison</td><td>boxplot(values ~ group, data=df)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Scatter Plot</td><td>Relationship between 2 variables</td><td>plot(x, y, main="Title")</td></tr>
<tr><td>Heat Map</td><td>2D pattern across categories</td><td>heatmap(as.matrix(data))</td></tr>
<tr><td>Pair Plot</td><td>All pairwise relationships at once</td><td>pairs(df) or GGally::ggpairs(df)</td></tr>
</table>
</div></div>
</div>

